<paragraph blockId="5.[136,1452,460,775]" pageId="5" pageNumber="78">
Etymology:—‘ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="W. R. Lin &amp; P. H. Wang" authorityYear="2022" box="[306,488,460,486]" class="Agaricomycetes" family="Hydnodontaceae" genus="Scytinopogon" kingdom="Fungi" order="Trechisporales" pageId="5" pageNumber="78" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="cryptomerioides">
<emphasis box="[306,488,460,486]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="78">cryptomerioides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
’ refers to the forest habitat of the fungus and growth in association with the roots of 
<taxonomicName box="[136,386,496,522]" class="Pinopsida" family="Cupressaceae" genus="Cryptomeria" kingdom="Plantae" order="Pinales" pageId="5" pageNumber="78" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="japonica">
<emphasis box="[136,386,496,522]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="78">Cryptomeria japonica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The DNA of the fungus could be detected in the roots of 
<taxonomicName box="[1055,1187,496,522]" class="Pinopsida" family="Cupressaceae" genus="Cryptomeria" kingdom="Plantae" order="Pinales" pageId="5" pageNumber="78" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="japonica">
<emphasis box="[1055,1187,496,522]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="78">C. japonica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and the fruiting of this fungus is affected by thinning of 
<taxonomicName box="[522,655,532,558]" class="Pinopsida" family="Cupressaceae" genus="Cryptomeria" kingdom="Plantae" order="Pinales" pageId="5" pageNumber="78" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="japonica">
<emphasis box="[522,655,532,558]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="78">C. japonica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Lin 
<emphasis box="[723,781,532,558]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="78">et al.</emphasis>
unpublished data). These results indicated that the fungus grows in association with the roots of 
<taxonomicName box="[563,694,568,594]" class="Pinopsida" family="Cupressaceae" genus="Cryptomeria" kingdom="Plantae" order="Pinales" pageId="5" pageNumber="78" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="japonica">
<emphasis box="[563,694,568,594]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="78">C. japonica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[136,1452,460,775]" pageId="5" pageNumber="78">
Description:— 
<emphasis box="[356,485,604,630]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="78">Basidiomes</emphasis>
coralloid, up to 
<quantity box="[670,804,604,631]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.0" metricValueMax="11.0" metricValueMin="5.0" pageId="5" pageNumber="78" unit="mm" value="80.0" valueMax="110.0" valueMin="50.0">50–110 mm</quantity>
in height, branched, tufts arising from a common stem or cluster of stems, white, cream or tan when fresh, rather tough, subcoriaceous, brown on drying, caespitose, gregarious or solitary on sandy loam soil. 
<emphasis box="[479,535,676,702]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="78">Stipe</emphasis>
up to 10–30 × 
<quantity box="[702,797,676,703]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.5" metricValueMax="6.0" metricValueMin="1.0" pageId="5" pageNumber="78" unit="mm" value="3.5" valueMax="6.0" valueMin="1.0">1–6 mm</quantity>
, cylindric or sub-compressed, thick, arising from a tangled mass of mycelial strands. 
<emphasis box="[438,544,712,738]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="78">Branches</emphasis>
dichotomous or polytomous, flattened, generally branched from the base. The mycelium was associated with the roots of 
<taxonomicName box="[619,750,748,774]" class="Pinopsida" family="Cupressaceae" genus="Cryptomeria" kingdom="Plantae" order="Pinales" pageId="5" pageNumber="78" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="japonica">
<emphasis box="[619,750,748,774]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="78">C. japonica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[765,853,748,774]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="5.[136,229,1480,1502]" captionTargetBox="[310,1278,796,1444]" captionTargetId="figure-226@5.[310,1278,796,1453]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 2. A: Basidiomes of Scytinopogon cryptomerioides in natural habitat. B: Basidiome of S. cryptomerioides associated with roots of C. japonica (holotype, 0906RK10-23) (Bar: 1 cm). Photos by: W.R. Lin." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6673267" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6673267/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="78">Fig. 2B</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6673267" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6673267" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6673267/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="78" startId="5.[136,229,1480,1502]" targetBox="[310,1278,796,1444]" targetPageId="5">
<paragraph blockId="5.[136,1451,1480,1539]" pageId="5" pageNumber="78">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[136,253,1480,1502]" pageId="5" pageNumber="78">FIGURE 2.</emphasis>
A: Basidiomes of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="W. R. Lin &amp; P. H. Wang" authorityYear="2022" box="[431,723,1481,1502]" class="Agaricomycetes" family="Hydnodontaceae" genus="Scytinopogon" kingdom="Fungi" order="Trechisporales" pageId="5" pageNumber="78" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="cryptomerioides">
<emphasis box="[431,723,1481,1502]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="78">Scytinopogon cryptomerioides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in natural habitat. B: Basidiome of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="W. R. Lin &amp; P. H. Wang" authorityYear="2022" box="[1065,1245,1481,1502]" class="Agaricomycetes" family="Hydnodontaceae" genus="Scytinopogon" kingdom="Fungi" order="Trechisporales" pageId="5" pageNumber="78" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="cryptomerioides">
<emphasis box="[1065,1245,1481,1502]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="78">S. cryptomerioides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
associated with roots of 
<taxonomicName box="[162,274,1517,1538]" class="Pinopsida" family="Cupressaceae" genus="Cryptomeria" kingdom="Plantae" order="Pinales" pageId="5" pageNumber="78" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="japonica">
<emphasis box="[162,274,1517,1538]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="78">C. japonica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(holotype, 0906RK10-23) (Bar: 1 cm). Photos by: W.R. Lin.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="5.[136,1452,1585,2080]" pageId="5" pageNumber="78">
<emphasis box="[189,356,1585,1611]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="78">Hyphal system</emphasis>
monomitic; tramal hyphae smooth, thin-walled, colorless, 2–3 μm wide, ampullate at septa, all with clamps. 
<emphasis box="[293,379,1621,1647]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="78">Basidia</emphasis>
formed laterally from generative hyphae, with basal clamp (
<figureCitation box="[1090,1162,1621,1648]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="7.[136,229,1612,1634]" captionTargetBox="[151,1419,365,1587]" captionTargetId="figure-90@7.[151,1436,353,1587]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 5. Microscopic structure of basidia of Scytinopogon cryptomerioides (holotype, 0906RK10-23) (Bar: 5 μm). Drawing by W. R. Lin." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6673273" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6673273/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="78">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
). Basidia 35–42 × 5.5–6 μm, clavate, finely granular-vacuolate, with four conical sterigmata (mostly 3–4 μm long). 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hubner" authorityYear="1819" box="[1200,1293,1657,1683]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Cystidia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="78" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1200,1293,1657,1683]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="78">Cystidia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
absent (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="6.[136,229,1978,2000]" captionTargetBox="[236,1351,1138,1947]" captionTargetId="figure-74@6.[228,1359,1134,1954]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 4. Scanning electron micrographs of Scytinopogon cryptomerioides—Development of basidiospores.A: spherical enlargement of the sterigma apex. B: spherical enlargement of the basidiospore. C: beginning formation of ornamentation. D: depressions of the hilar appendices of spores. Bars: 1 μm. Specimen number: 0906RK6-10. Photos by: W. R. Lin." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6673271" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6673271/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="78">Figs. 4A</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[185,201,1693,1720]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="7.[136,229,1612,1634]" captionTargetBox="[151,1419,365,1587]" captionTargetId="figure-90@7.[151,1436,353,1587]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 5. Microscopic structure of basidia of Scytinopogon cryptomerioides (holotype, 0906RK10-23) (Bar: 5 μm). Drawing by W. R. Lin." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6673273" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6673273/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="78">5</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis box="[223,381,1693,1719]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="78">Basidiospores</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[397,518,1693,1719]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="6.[136,229,1050,1072]" captionTargetBox="[233,1356,195,1016]" captionTargetId="figure-39@6.[227,1360,187,1023]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 3. Scanning electron micrographs of Scytinopogon cryptomerioides (0906RK6-10). A: basidiospores. B: basidiospores. C–E: apices of basidia. Bars:A, D, E 1 μm; B, C 2 μm. Photos by: W. R. Lin." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6673269" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6673269/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="78">Fig. 3A–B</figureCitation>
) 4.0–6.0 × 3–3.5 μm, colorless, ellipsoid, echinulate or verrucose with acute warts or spines 0.5–0.7 μm long, slightly angular, inamyloid and cyanophilous. Hilar appendix small, obscured by spore ornamentation. Basidiospore development (
<figureCitation box="[627,695,1765,1791]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="6.[136,229,1978,2000]" captionTargetBox="[236,1351,1138,1947]" captionTargetId="figure-74@6.[228,1359,1134,1954]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 4. Scanning electron micrographs of Scytinopogon cryptomerioides—Development of basidiospores.A: spherical enlargement of the sterigma apex. B: spherical enlargement of the basidiospore. C: beginning formation of ornamentation. D: depressions of the hilar appendices of spores. Bars: 1 μm. Specimen number: 0906RK6-10. Photos by: W. R. Lin." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6673271" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6673271/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="78">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
) starts with a spherical enlargement of the sterigma apex to form a basidiospore primordium 0.6–0.8 μm in diameter (
<figureCitation box="[715,808,1801,1827]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="6.[136,229,1978,2000]" captionTargetBox="[236,1351,1138,1947]" captionTargetId="figure-74@6.[228,1359,1134,1954]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 4. Scanning electron micrographs of Scytinopogon cryptomerioides—Development of basidiospores.A: spherical enlargement of the sterigma apex. B: spherical enlargement of the basidiospore. C: beginning formation of ornamentation. D: depressions of the hilar appendices of spores. Bars: 1 μm. Specimen number: 0906RK6-10. Photos by: W. R. Lin." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6673271" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6673271/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="78">Fig. 4A</figureCitation>
). The basidiospore initially grows asymmetrically on its abaxial side (
<figureCitation box="[284,372,1837,1863]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="6.[136,229,1978,2000]" captionTargetBox="[236,1351,1138,1947]" captionTargetId="figure-74@6.[228,1359,1134,1954]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 4. Scanning electron micrographs of Scytinopogon cryptomerioides—Development of basidiospores.A: spherical enlargement of the sterigma apex. B: spherical enlargement of the basidiospore. C: beginning formation of ornamentation. D: depressions of the hilar appendices of spores. Bars: 1 μm. Specimen number: 0906RK6-10. Photos by: W. R. Lin." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6673271" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6673271/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="78">Fig. 4B</figureCitation>
). The spherical body enlargements, the hilar appendices, and the ornamentation formation of the basidiospore are shown in 
<figureCitation box="[435,554,1873,1899]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="6.[136,229,1978,2000]" captionTargetBox="[236,1351,1138,1947]" captionTargetId="figure-74@6.[228,1359,1134,1954]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 4. Scanning electron micrographs of Scytinopogon cryptomerioides—Development of basidiospores.A: spherical enlargement of the sterigma apex. B: spherical enlargement of the basidiospore. C: beginning formation of ornamentation. D: depressions of the hilar appendices of spores. Bars: 1 μm. Specimen number: 0906RK6-10. Photos by: W. R. Lin." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6673271" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6673271/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="78">Fig. 4B–C</figureCitation>
, the depression of the hilar appendices in 
<figureCitation box="[1023,1112,1873,1899]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="6.[136,229,1978,2000]" captionTargetBox="[236,1351,1138,1947]" captionTargetId="figure-74@6.[228,1359,1134,1954]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 4. Scanning electron micrographs of Scytinopogon cryptomerioides—Development of basidiospores.A: spherical enlargement of the sterigma apex. B: spherical enlargement of the basidiospore. C: beginning formation of ornamentation. D: depressions of the hilar appendices of spores. Bars: 1 μm. Specimen number: 0906RK6-10. Photos by: W. R. Lin." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6673271" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6673271/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="78">Fig. 4D</figureCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[136,1452,1585,2080]" pageId="5" pageNumber="78">
Habitat and distribution:—terrestrial, solitary, gregarious, or caespitose on sandy loam soil (
<figureCitation box="[1222,1313,1909,1935]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="5.[136,229,1480,1502]" captionTargetBox="[310,1278,796,1444]" captionTargetId="figure-226@5.[310,1278,796,1453]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 2. A: Basidiomes of Scytinopogon cryptomerioides in natural habitat. B: Basidiome of S. cryptomerioides associated with roots of C. japonica (holotype, 0906RK10-23) (Bar: 1 cm). Photos by: W.R. Lin." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6673267" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6673267/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="78">Fig. 2A</figureCitation>
). This taxon was collected on the ground in forests dominated by 
<taxonomicName box="[717,964,1945,1971]" class="Pinopsida" family="Cupressaceae" genus="Cryptomeria" kingdom="Plantae" order="Pinales" pageId="5" pageNumber="78" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="japonica">
<emphasis box="[717,964,1945,1971]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="78">Cryptomeria japonica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
at an elevation of 
<quantity box="[1166,1309,1945,1972]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.35" metricValueMax="2.1" metricValueMin="0.6" pageId="5" pageNumber="78" unit="m" value="1350.0" valueMax="2100.0" valueMin="600.0">600–2100 m</quantity>
. The fruiting lasted for 2 to 3 months. The mycelium was associated with the roots of 
<taxonomicName box="[956,1087,1981,2007]" class="Pinopsida" family="Cupressaceae" genus="Cryptomeria" kingdom="Plantae" order="Pinales" pageId="5" pageNumber="78" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="japonica">
<emphasis box="[956,1087,1981,2007]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="78">C. japonica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<bibRefCitation author="Lin, W. R. &amp; Wang, P. H. &amp; Chen, M. C. &amp; Kuo, Y. L. &amp; Chiang, P. N. &amp; Wang, M. K." box="[1102,1287,1981,2008]" pageId="5" pageNumber="78" pagination="183 - 193" refId="ref5570" refString="Lin, W. R., Wang, P. H., Chen, M. C., Kuo, Y. L., Chiang, P. N. &amp; Wang, M. K. (2015) The impacts of thinning on the fruiting of saprophytic fungi in Cryptomeria japonica plantations in central Taiwan. Forest Ecology and Management 336: 183 - 193. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / j. foreco. 2014.10.022" type="journal article" year="2015">
Lin 
<emphasis box="[1148,1198,1981,2007]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="78">et al</emphasis>
. (2015)
</bibRefCitation>
found that the fruiting of saprophytic fungi was negatively affected by tree-cutting in 
<taxonomicName box="[923,1053,2017,2043]" class="Pinopsida" family="Cupressaceae" genus="Cryptomeria" kingdom="Plantae" order="Pinales" pageId="5" pageNumber="78" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="japonica">
<emphasis box="[923,1053,2017,2043]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="78">C. japonica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
plantations, whether this is the case for 
<taxonomicName authorityName="W. R. Lin &amp; P. H. Wang" authorityYear="2022" box="[176,386,2053,2080]" class="Agaricomycetes" family="Hydnodontaceae" genus="Scytinopogon" kingdom="Fungi" order="Trechisporales" pageId="5" pageNumber="78" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="cryptomerioides">
<emphasis box="[176,190,2053,2079]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="78">S</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[204,386,2053,2079]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="78">cryptomerioides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
could be the subject of another study.
</paragraph>
